# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexis-st-martin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] On June 6, 1822, St-Martin was accidentally shot with a musket at close range at the fur trading post on Mackinac Island.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] The charge of the musket shot left a hole through his side that healed to form a fistula aperture into his stomach.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] William Beaumont, a US Army surgeon stationed at a nearby army post, treated the wound.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Although St-Martin was a healthy young man in his 20s, he was not expected to recover due to the severity of his wound.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Beaumont explains in a later paper that the shot blew off fragments of St-Martin's muscles and broke a few of his ribs.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] After bleeding him and giving him a cathartic, Beaumont marked St-Martin's progress.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] For the next 17 days, all food he ate re-emerged from his new gastric fistula.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Finally after 17 days, the food began to stay in St-Martin's stomach and his bowels began to return to their natural functions.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] When the wound healed itself, the edge of the hole in the stomach had attached itself to the edge of the hole in the skin, creating a permanent gastric fistula.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Beaumont continued to experiment on St-Martin off and on until 1833, performing an estimated 200 experiments over a period of 10 years.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] St-Martin allowed the experiments to be conducted, not as an act to repay Beaumont for keeping him alive but rather because Beaumont had the illiterate St-Martin sign a contract to work as a servant.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Beaumont published an account of his experiments in 1838 as *Experiments and Observations on the Gastric Juice, and the Physiology of Digestion*.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Beaumont drew 51 conclusions about digestion based on his observations of Alexis St-Martin and his related research.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Many of Beaumont's ideas were revolutionary for their time.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] He determined that vegetables were digested more slowly than meat, that milk coagulated early in the digestive process, and that digestion is aided by a churning motion within the stomach.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Beaumont's research into gastric juices was very advanced for the time.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] His work confirmed William Prout's theory that gastric juices contained hydrochloric acid, and he further discovered that gastric juice was secreted by the stomach lining.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Without Alexis St-Martin, none of this work would have been possible.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Eventually Beaumont and St-Martin parted ways: St-Martin wrote to Beaumont from Berthier, Canada, on June 26, 1834, refusing to return to Beaumont.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] As an army doctor, Beaumont was posted to the Jefferson Barracks in St.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] He became Professor of Surgery in the Medical Department of Saint Louis University in 1837 and resigned from the army in 1839.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Repeatedly, Beaumont tried to get St-Martin to move to St.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] When Alexis St-Martin died at Saint-Thomas, Quebec, in 1880, his family delayed his burial until the body began to decompose in order to prevent his "resurrection" by medical men, some of whom wished to perform an autopsy or remove the stomach.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] Alexis Bidagan *dit* St-Martin is buried at Saint-Thomas Parish Cemetery in Joliette, Quebec, Canada.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] The eminent physician Sir William Osler took a great interest in retracing the details of this early incident in the history of gastric physiology and published his research in the form of a well-known essay entitled *A Backwoods Physiologist*.
[src:alexis-st-martin/alexis-st-martin] He also attempted to have the famous stomach placed in the Army Medical Museum in Washington, DC.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The modern term *phlebotomy* refers to the drawing of blood for laboratory analysis or blood transfusion.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] *Therapeutic phlebotomy* refers to the drawing of a unit of blood in specific cases like hemochromatosis, polycythemia vera, porphyria cutanea tarda, etc., to reduce the number of red blood cells.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The traditional medical practice of bloodletting is considered a pseudoscience, though the method is still commonly used in forms of alternative medicine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Passages from the Ebers Papyrus may indicate that bloodletting by scarification was an accepted practice in Ancient Egypt.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Egyptian burials have been reported to contain bloodletting instruments.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] According to some accounts, the Egyptians based the idea on their observations of the hippopotamus, confusing its red secretions with blood and believing that it scratched itself to relieve distress.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] In Greece, bloodletting was in use in the 5th century BC during the lifetime of Hippocrates, who mentions this practice but generally relied on dietary techniques.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Erasistratus, however, theorized that many diseases were caused by plethoras, or overabundances, in the blood and advised that these plethoras be treated, initially, by exercise, sweating, reduced food intake, and vomiting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] But his student Herophilus supported bloodletting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] A contemporary Greek physician, Archagathus, one of the first to practice in Rome, also believed in the value of bloodletting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] "Bleeding" a patient to health was modeled on the process of menstruation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Hippocrates believed that menstruation functioned to "purge women of bad humors".
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] During the Roman Empire, the Greek physician Galen, who subscribed to the teachings of Hippocrates, advocated physician-initiated bloodletting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The popularity of bloodletting in the classical Mediterranean world was reinforced by the ideas of Galen, after he discovered that not only veins but also arteries were filled with blood, not air as was commonly believed at the time.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] There were two key concepts in his system of bloodletting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The first was that blood was created and then used up; it did not circulate, and so it could "stagnate" in the extremities.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The second was that humoral balance was the basis of illness or health, the four humors being blood, phlegm, black bile, and yellow bile, relating to the four Greek classical elements of air, water, earth, and fire respectively.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Galen believed that blood was the dominant humor and the one in most need of control.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] In order to balance the humors, a physician would either remove "excess" blood (plethora) from the patient or give them an emetic to induce vomiting, or a diuretic to induce urination.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Galen created a complex system of how much blood should be removed based on the patient's age, constitution, the season, the weather and the place.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] "Do-it-yourself" bleeding instructions following these systems were developed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Symptoms of plethora were believed to include fever, apoplexy, and headache.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The blood to be let was of a specific nature determined by the disease: either arterial or venous, and distant or close to the area of the body affected.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] He linked different blood vessels with different organs, according to their supposed drainage.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] For example, the vein in the right hand would be let for liver problems and the vein in the left hand for problems with the spleen.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The more severe the disease, the more blood would be let.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Fevers required copious amounts of bloodletting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] A physician holds the patient's arm straight, while blood streams into a bowl.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The knife used to cut the wound is on the table, a tourniquet on the floor.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The Talmud recommended a specific day of the week and days of the month for bloodletting in the Shabbat tractate.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] During medieval times bleeding charts were common, showing specific bleeding sites on the body in alignment with the planets and zodiacs.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Islamic medical authors also advised bloodletting, particularly for fevers.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] It was practised according to seasons and certain phases of the Moon in the lunar calendar.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The practice was probably passed by the Greeks with the translation of ancient texts to Arabic and is different from bloodletting by cupping mentioned in the traditions of Muhammad.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] When Muslim theories became known in the Latin-speaking countries of Europe, bloodletting became more widespread.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Together with cautery, it was central to Arabic surgery; the key texts *Kitab al-Qanun* and especially **Al-Tasrif li-man 'ajaza 'an al-ta'lif** both recommended it.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] It was also known in Ayurvedic medicine, described in the *Susruta Samhita*.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting became a main technique of heroic medicine, a traumatic and destructive collection of medical practices that emerged in the 18th century.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Even after the humoral system fell into disuse, the practice was continued by surgeons and barber-surgeons.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Though the bloodletting was often *recommended* by physicians, it was carried out by barbers.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] This led to the distinction between physicians and surgeons.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The red-and-white-striped pole of the barbershop, still in use today, is derived from this practice: the red symbolizes blood while the white symbolizes the bandages.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting was used to "treat" a wide range of diseases, becoming a standard treatment for almost every ailment, and was practiced prophylactically as well as therapeutically.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] A number of different methods were employed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The most common was *phlebotomy*, or *venesection* (often called "breathing a vein"), in which blood was drawn from one or more of the larger external veins, such as those in the forearm or neck.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] In *arteriotomy*, an artery was punctured, although generally only in the temples.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] In *scarification* (not to be confused with scarification, a method of body modification), the "superficial" vessels were attacked, often using a syringe, a spring-loaded lancet, or a glass cup that contained heated air, producing a vacuum within (see fire cupping).
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] There was also a specific bloodletting tool called a *scarificator*, used primarily in 19th century medicine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] It has a spring-loaded mechanism with gears that snaps the blades out through slits in the front cover and back in, in a circular motion.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The case is cast brass, and the mechanism and blades steel.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] One knife bar gear has slipped teeth, turning the blades in a different direction than those on the other bars.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The last photo and the diagram show the depth adjustment bar at the back and sides.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The withdrawal of so much blood as to induce syncope (fainting) was considered beneficial, and many sessions would only end when the patient began to swoon.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] William Harvey disproved the basis of the practice in 1628, and the introduction of scientific medicine, *la méthode numérique*, allowed Pierre Charles Alexandre Louis to demonstrate that phlebotomy was entirely ineffective in the treatment of pneumonia and various fevers in the 1830s.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Nevertheless, in 1838, a lecturer at the Royal College of Physicians would still state that "blood-letting is a remedy which, when judiciously employed, it is hardly possible to estimate too highly", and Louis was dogged by the sanguinary Broussais, who could recommend leeches fifty at a time.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] During this era, bloodletting was used to treat almost every disease.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting was even used to treat most forms of hemorrhaging such as nosebleed, excessive menstruation, or hemorrhoidal bleeding.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Before surgery or at the onset of childbirth, blood was removed to prevent inflammation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Before amputation, it was customary to remove a quantity of blood equal to the amount believed to circulate in the limb that was to be removed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] There were also theories that bloodletting would cure "heartsickness" and "heartbreak".
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] A French physician, Jacques Ferrand wrote a book in 1623 on the uses of bloodletting to cure a broken heart.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] He recommended bloodletting to the point of heart failure (literal).
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Leeches became especially popular in the early 19th century.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] In the 1830s, the French imported about 40 million leeches a year for medical purposes, and in the next decade, England imported 6 million leeches a year from France alone.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Through the early decades of the century, hundreds of millions of leeches were used by physicians throughout Europe.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting was also popular in the young United States of America, where Benjamin Rush (a signatory of the Declaration of Independence) saw the state of the arteries as the key to disease, recommending levels of bloodletting that were high even for the time.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] George Washington asked to be bled heavily after he developed a throat infection from weather exposure.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Within a ten-hour period, a total of 124–126 ounces (3.75 liters) of blood was withdrawn prior to his death from a throat infection in 1799.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The psychological benefit of bloodletting to the patient (a placebo effect) may sometimes have outweighed the physiological problems it caused.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting slowly lost favour during the 19th century, after French physician Dr.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Pierre Louis conducted an experiment in which he studied the effect of bloodletting on pneumonia patients.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] A number of other ineffective or harmful treatments were available as placebos—mesmerism, various processes involving the new technology of electricity, many potions, tonics, and elixirs.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Yet, bloodletting persisted during the 19th century partly because it was readily available to people of any socioeconomic status.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Barbara Ehrenreich and Deirdre English write that the popularity of bloodletting and heroic medicine in general was because of a need to justify medical billing.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Traditional healing techniques had been mostly practiced by women within a non-commercial family or village setting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] As male doctors suppressed these techniques, they found it difficult to quantify various "amounts" of healing to charge for, and difficult to convince patients to pay for it.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Because bloodletting seemed active and dramatic, it helped convince patients the doctor had something tangible to sell.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting gradually declined in popularity over the course of the 19th century, becoming rather uncommon in most places, before its validity was thoroughly debated.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] In the medical community of Edinburgh, bloodletting was abandoned in practice before it was challenged in theory, a contradiction highlighted by physician-physiologist John Hughes Bennett.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Authorities such as Austin Flint I, Hiram Corson, and William Osler became prominent supporters of bloodletting in the 1880s and onwards, disputing Bennett's premise that bloodletting had fallen into disuse because it did not work.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] These advocates framed bloodletting as an orthodox medical practice, to be used in spite of its general unpopularity.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Some physicians considered bloodletting useful for a more limited range of purposes, such as to "clear out" infected or weakened blood or its ability to "cause hæmorrhages to cease"—as evidenced in a call for a "fair trial for blood-letting as a remedy" in 1871.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Some researchers used statistical methods for evaluating treatment effectiveness to discourage bloodletting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] But at the same time, publications by Philip Pye-Smith and others defended bloodletting on scientific grounds.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting persisted into the 20th century and was recommended in the 1923 edition of the textbook *The Principles and Practice of Medicine*.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The textbook was originally written by Sir William Osler and continued to be published in new editions under new authors following Osler's death in 1919.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting was once thought to reduce inflammation, boost immunity, and improve circulation by aiding in the detoxification of the blood circulating throughout the body.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Over time, however, bloodletting's harmful impacts made the practice a less preferable form of medicine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Not only was bloodletting generally ineffective, it also commonly led to significant blood loss.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] High loss of blood made patients highly susceptible to infection/sepsis or the formation of a hematoma.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Additionally, bloodletting also caused anemia, leading the patient to feel weak, tired, or even go unconscious.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The harmful effects did not stop there; in severe cases, bloodletting had the potential to cause deadly hypovolemic shock.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] As the medical world advanced, these deadly effects made the practice of bloodletting fade in popularity.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Therapeutic phlebotomy is used today in the treatment of a few diseases, including hemochromatosis, sickle cell disease, porphyria cutanea tarda, nonalcoholic fatty liver disease, and polycythemia.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] It is practiced by specifically trained practitioners in hospitals using modern techniques and a relatively safe procedure that depletes iron stores in the body.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] In most cases, phlebotomy now refers to the removal of *small* quantities of blood for diagnostic purposes and is an important procedure in the US.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] According to an academic article posted in the *Journal of Infusion Nursing* with data published in 2010, the primary use of phlebotomy is to take blood that would be reinfused back into a person (blood donation).
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] However, in the case of hemochromatosis, bloodletting (by venipuncture) has become the mainstay treatment option.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Therapeutic phlebotomy is a cost effective way to remove excess iron in blood for patients that have hemochromatosis.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Therapeutic uses of bloodletting were reported in 60 distinct cultures/ethnic groups in the HRAF database, present in all inhabited continents.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting has also been reported in 15 of the 60 cultures in the probability sample files (PSF) list.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The PSF is a subset of eHRAF data that includes only one culture from each of 60 macro-culture areas around the world.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] The prevalence of bloodletting in PSF controls for pseudo-replication linked to common ancestry, suggesting that bloodletting has independently emerged many times.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting is varied in its practices cross-culturally, for example, in native Alaskan culture bloodletting was practiced for different indications, using different tools, on different body areas, by different people, and it was explained by different medical theories.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] According to Helena Miton et al.'s analysis of the HRAF database and other sources, there are several cross-cultural patterns in bloodletting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] In a transmission chain experiment done on people living in the US through Amazon Mechanical Turk, stories about bloodletting in a non-affected area were much more likely to transition into stories about bloodletting being administered near the area in pain than vice versa.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] This suggests that colocalized bloodletting could be a cultural attractor and is more likely to be culturally transmitted, even among people in the US who are likely more familiar with non-colocalized bloodletting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] Bloodletting as a concept is thought to be a cultural attractor, or an intrinsically attractive / culturally transmissible concept.
[src:alexis-st-martin/bloodletting] This could explain bloodletting's independent cross-cultural emergence and common cross-cultural traits.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Those who practiced the act of body snatching and sale of corpses during this period were commonly referred to as **resurrectionists** or **resurrection men**.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Resurrectionists in the United Kingdom, who often worked in teams and who primarily targeted more recently dug graves, would be hired in order to provide medical institutions and practitioners with a supply of fresh cadavers for the purpose of anatomical study.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Despite a significant decline in body snatching as a practice, there are contemporary instances of body snatching.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In some rural areas, ghost marriages are popular.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] When an unmarried man dies, his family will find a female corpse to bury him together with.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] As a result, female corpses are often stolen.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Before the Anatomy Act 1832 (2 & 3 Will.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] 75), the only legal supply of corpses for anatomical purposes in the UK were those condemned to death and dissection by the courts.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Dissections, the main way doctors aimed to gain understanding, required fresh corpses.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Those who were sentenced to dissection by the courts were often guilty of capital crimes, such as murder, burglary, rape, and arson.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] However, in 1832, Parliament of the United Kingdom passed the Anatomy Act 1832, which gave doctors and medical students the right to dissect donated bodies for education and research purposes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Although this act was created to stop the illegal tradeoff of corpses, it did not provide near enough corpses needed by medical schools annually, which could be up to 500 in number.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This led to increased numbers of body snatching in the United Kingdom.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Interfering with a grave was a misdemeanour at common law, and therefore punishable only with a fine and imprisonment rather than penal transportation or execution.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] However, dissection of these bodies and theft of items within the graves was illegal.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This caused the body snatchers to only take the body and leave everything else behind in the grave.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Medical students and staff did not ask where the bodies came from.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The trade was a sufficiently lucrative business to run the risk of detection, particularly as the authorities tended to ignore what they considered a necessary evil.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Body snatchers had a limited period in which they could dig up a body before it began decomposing, so that the body could be embalmed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] They had to remain undetectable while exhuming the bodies and transporting them from the gravesites to the medical facilities.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] There were several methods used in obtaining a corpse.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Once such was digging down to the head-end of the coffin and breaking the top open, using a rope or hook to grab the body by its neck and hoist it out of the coffin.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Body snatchers were careful to put any clothing, jewelry, and personal belongings back into the coffin before refilling the hole, and trying to smooth out the gravesite as much as possible to look undisturbed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] What distinguished body snatching from grave-robbing was the practice of returning belongings to the gravesite before moving on.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Removing belongings from the corpse would make them liable to prosecution.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Body snatching became so prevalent in the UK that it was not unusual for relatives and friends of someone who had just died to watch over the body until burial, and then to keep watch over the grave *after* burial, to stop it being violated.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Iron coffins, too, were used frequently, or the graves were protected by a framework of iron bars called *mortsafes*, well-preserved examples of which may still be seen in Greyfriars churchyard, Edinburgh.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In relation to body snatching, murder for the purpose of selling the corpses to medical schools also occurred.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The term "burked" was coined after William Burke, an Irishman, was found guilty of murdering and selling the bodies of at least 16 people.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Burke would pinch the nose of his victims and lay on their chest so that there was no physical damage to the bodies.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] He was hanged and dissected for his crimes in 1829.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Many laws passed by Parliament covered body snatching or similar practices.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Human Tissue Act 2004 created the first overarching law that required informed personal consent to be needed for body or organ donation within medical facilities.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Body snatchers generally worked in small groups, which scouted and pillaged fresh graves.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Fresh graves were generally given preference since the earth had not yet settled, thus making digging easier.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The removed earth was often shoveled onto canvas tarp laid by the grave, so the nearby grounds were undisturbed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Digging commenced at the head of the grave, clear to the coffin.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The remaining earth on the coffin provided a counterweight which snapped the partially covered coffin lid (which was covered in sacking to muffle noise) as crowbars or hooks pulled the lid free at the head of the coffin.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Usually, the body would be disrobed–the garments thrown back into the coffin before the earth was put back into place.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Resurrectionists have also been known to hire women to act the part of grieving relatives and to claim the bodies of dead at poorhouses.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Women were also hired to attend funerals as grieving mourners; their purpose was to ascertain any hardships the body snatchers may later encounter during the disinterment.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Bribed servants would sometimes offer body snatchers access to their dead master or mistress lying in state; the removed body would be replaced with weights.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Although medical research and education lagged in the United States compared to medical colleges' European counterparts, the interest in anatomical dissection grew in the United States.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Philadelphia, Baltimore, New York with several medical schools, were renowned for body snatching activity: all locales provided plenty of cadavers.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Finding subjects for dissection proved to be "morally troubling" for students of anatomy.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] As late as the mid-19th century, John Gorham Coffin, a prominent aptly named professor and medical physician, wondered how any ethical physician could participate in the traffic of dead bodies.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Charles Knowlton (1800–1850) was imprisoned for two months in the Worcester (Massachusetts) County Jail for "illegal dissection" in 1824, a couple of months after graduating with distinction from Dartmouth Medical School.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] His thesis defended dissection on the utilitarian basis that "value of any art or science should be determined by the tendency it has to increase the happiness, or to diminish the misery, of mankind".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Knowlton called for doctors to relieve "public prejudice" by donating their own bodies for dissection.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The body of Ohio congressman John Scott Harrison, son of William Henry Harrison, was snatched in 1878 for Ohio Medical College, and discovered by his son John Harrison, brother of President Benjamin Harrison.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Large, gated, centralized cemeteries, which sometimes employed armed guards, emerged as a response to grave-robbing fears.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Gated, "high-security" cemeteries were also a response to the discovery that many old urban and rural burying grounds were found to be practically empty of their human contents when downtown areas were re-developed and old pioneer cemeteries moved, as in Indianapolis.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The demand for cadavers for human dissection grew as medical schools were established in the United States.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This was due to the demand for students to have more first-hand experiences with multiple cadavers, rather than observing dissections on only one specimen.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The sudden advances in surgery were what brought on this demand for cadavers for medical school students to learn more about internal anatomy.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Between the years of 1758 and 1788, only 63 of the 3500 physicians in the Colonies had studied abroad, namely at the University of Edinburgh Medical School.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Study of anatomy legitimized the medical field, setting it apart from homeopathic and botanical studies.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Later, in 1847, physicians formed the American Medical Association, in an effort to differentiate between the "true science" of medicine and "the assumptions of ignorance and empiricism" based on an education without the experience of human dissection.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In addition, the medical community wanted to grow medical students’ knowledge and improve their education by creating a licensing system to terminate those who only went to medical school for pleasantry.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] By requiring training in anatomy as a prerequisite, this demanded the need for cadavers for medical school students for their graduation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The University of Pennsylvania was the first medical school in America in the 18th century.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 1762, John Morgan and William Shippen Jr. founded the medical department of University of Pennsylvania.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Shippen put an advertisement in the Pennsylvania Gazette in November 1762 announcing his lectures about the "art of dissecting, injections, etc." The cost was "five pistoles".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 1765, his house was attacked by a mob, claiming the doctor had desecrated a church's burying ground.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The doctor denied this and made known that he only used bodies of "suicides, executed felons, and now and then one from the Potter's Field".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Later in the 19th century, this school issued an anatomy law that would be state-wide, which was issued around the statement of grave-robbing.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This was due to an organized group of grave robbers in Philadelphia.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Senator William James McKnight was the person behind the upbringing of the state-wide anatomy law and was involved in grave-robbing himself after this act was finalized to the public.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In Boston, medical students faced similar issues with procuring subjects for dissection.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] These experiences gave John Warren the experience he needed to begin his lectures on anatomy in 1781.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Ebenezer Hersey, a physician, left Harvard College £1,000 for the creation of a Professorship in Anatomy in 1770.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] A year earlier, John Warren and his friends had created a secret anatomic society.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This society's purpose was to participate in anatomic dissection, using cadavers that they themselves procured.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The group's name was the "Spunkers"; however, speaking or writing the name was prohibited.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Often the group used shovels to obtain fresh corpses for its anatomical study.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Harvard Medical School was established November 22, 1782; John Warren was elected Professor of Anatomy and Surgery.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] When his son was in the college in 1796, the peaceful times provided few subjects.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] John Collins Warren Jr. wrote: "Having understood that a man without relations was to be buried in the North Burying-Ground, I formed a party ...
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] John Warren's quest for subjects led him to consult with his colleague, W.E.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Warren later enlisted the help of an old family friend, John Revere (son of Paul Revere) to procure subjects for dissection.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Revere called upon John Godman who suggested that Warren employ the services of James Henderson, "a trusty old friend and servant" who could "at any time, and almost to any number, obtain the articles you desire".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] During this time, there was an intense growth in New England of medical programs, which led to an increase in the need for anatomy cadavers.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] To keep a good supply of bodies became a difficult endeavor.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Students were sent away to Boston to seek subjects by grave-robbing.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This caused the public to get involved, and people began to set up grave watchers in graveyards to catch those who were snatching the bodies.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This led the students to move to New York to find potential bodies for cadavers, which at this time was not the safest option.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] People were going to jail and were fined for disturbing the gravesites.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Warren attempted to set up a cadaver provision system in Boston, similar to the systems already set up in New York and Philadelphia.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Public officials and burial-ground employees were routinely bribed for entrance to Potter's Field to get bodies.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] These types of places were favored by medical doctors who were in search of bodies to use for their dissections.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In New York, the bodies were divided into two groups–one group contained the bodies of those "most entitled to respect, or most likely to be called for by friends;" the other bodies were not exempt from exhumation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In Philadelphia's two public burying grounds, anatomists claimed bodies regularly, without consideration.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] These medical colleges were targeted by the general public opposed to body snatching, but the medical colleges fought back.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] One argument was that the medical colleges tried to see them as doing a good thing for the body, since most of the bodies that were taken were ones who did not have loved ones who grieved for them.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] These schools also attempted to convince the public that the bodies were from a source on the outside, rather than making it look like they had not got permission to take the body.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Public graveyards were not only arranged by social and economic standing, but also by race.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] "Bayley's dissecting tables, as well as those of Columbia College" often took bodies from the segregated section of Potter's Field, the Negroes Burying Ground.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Free blacks as well as slaves were buried there.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In the antebellum American South, bodies of enslaved workers were routinely used for anatomical study; in one case that has been studied, 80% of the corpses dissected at Transylvania University in the 1830s and 1840s were African American.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The ready availability of such bodies was cited as an incentive to enroll by Southern medical schools such as the Medical College of South Carolina.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] According to Hampden-Sydney, in Richmond, Virginia, "from the peculiarity of our institutions [slavery], materials [anatomical subjects] can be obtained in abundance, and we believe are not surpassed if equaled by any city in the country".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In fact the ready availability of [Black] corpses was cited as a reason why Richmond would be a good place to found a medical school.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The largest burial ground for enslaved and free people of color in the United States, the Shockoe Hill African Burying Ground is located in Richmond.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The bodies of criminals about to be executed were routinely requested of authorities for this purpose.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 1859, after John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry, Virginia, the University of Virginia and Winchester Medical College both requested the cadavers of those about to be hanged.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Four, three black (Shields Green, John Anthony Copeland Jr., and Jeremiah Anderson), and one white (John Brown's son Watson Brown), were obtained by the latter college.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In retaliation, Union troops burned Winchester Medical College in 1862; it never reopened.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In December 1882, it was discovered that six bodies had been disinterred from Lebanon Cemetery and were en route to Jefferson Medical College for dissection.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Philadelphia's African Americans were outraged, and a crowd assembled at the city morgue, where the discovered bodies had been sent.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Reportedly, one of the crowd urged the group to swear that they would seek revenge for those who participated in desecration of the graves.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Another man screamed when he discovered the body of his 29-year-old brother.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Philadelphia Press broke the story when a teary elderly woman identified her husband's body, whose burial she had afforded only by begging for the $22 at the wharves where he had been employed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Forbes was indicted, and the case led to passage of various Anatomical Acts.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] After the public hanging of 39 Dakota warriors in the aftermath of the Dakota War of 1862, a group of doctors removed the bodies under cover of darkness from their riverside grave, and each took some for himself.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Doctor William Worrall Mayo received the body of a warrior called "Cut Nose" and dissected it in the presence of other doctors.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] He then cleaned and articulated the skeleton and kept the bones in an iron kettle in his office.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] His sons received their first lessons in osteology from this skeleton.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] For many years Native American burial sites have been used as a place for body-snatching.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The bodies would be removed from their graves in the name of science.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Usually the bodies would be removed without consent from relatives, and there was no attempt to reach relatives.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] When these bodies are removed they are given to museums to be put on display.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Even if the tribe or relatives found out about the bodies being on display, they did not have the authority to have the bodies removed and returned.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In November 1990 the Native American Protection and Repatriation Act was signed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] During the early 1800s in Michigan the first Indian graves were robbed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Even though it was known at the time that Indian burial sites were considered sacred and should not be tampered with, many still dug up skulls and skeletal remains.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] During this incident two Indian burial sites were tampered with.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In the first site the entire body was taken while in the second the head was cut off.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Robert McKain was seen carrying the head back into the barracks with it wrapped in a handkerchief.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] It was shown that he had previously been accused of taking Indian heads from burial sites to give to paying surgeons.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] On February 21, 1788, the body of a woman was taken from the graveyard of New York City's Trinity Church.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] A hundred-dollar reward was offered by the rector of the church for information leading to the arrest of the perpetrators.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In the *Daily Advertiser*, many editorial letters were written about the incident: one such writer named Humanio warned that "lives may be forfeit ... should [the body snatchers] persist".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] There was cause for concern: body snatching was perceived to be "a daily occurrence".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] A famous case of body snatching in the United States was the Doctors' Riot of 1788.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] On April 13, a group of boys playing near the dissection room window of City Hospital peered in.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Accounts vary, but one of the boys saw what he thought were his mother's remains or that one of the students shook a dismembered arm at the boys.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Later, the mob reassembled to attack the jail where some of the medical students were being held for their safety.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The militia was called, but few showed; this was perhaps due to the militia sharing the public's outrage.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] One small troop was harassed and quickly withdrew.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Several prominent citizens–including Governor George Clinton; General Baron von Steuben, and John Jay–participated in the ranks of the militia protecting the doctors at the jail.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Three rioters were killed when the embattled militia opened fire on the mob, and when militia members from the countryside joined the defense, the mob threat quickly dissipated.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] To assuage the outraged public, legislation was enacted to thwart the activities of the body snatchers; eventually, anatomy acts, such as the Massachusetts Anatomy Act of 1831, allowed for the legalization of anatomy studies.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Prior to these measures allowing for more subjects, many tactics were employed to protect the bodies of relatives.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Police were engaged to watch the burying grounds but were often bribed or made drunk.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Spring guns were set in the coffins, and poorer families would leave items like a stone or a blade of grass or a shell to show whether the grave was tampered with or not.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In his collection of Boston police force details, Edward Savage made notes of a reward offer on April 13, 1814: "The selectmen offer $100 reward for arrest of grave-robbers at South Burying-Ground".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Iron fences were constructed around many burying grounds as a deterrent to body snatchers.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] "Burglar proof grave vaults made of steel" were sold with the promise that loved ones' remains would not be one of the 40,000 bodies "mutilated every year on dissecting tables in medical colleges in the United States".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The medical appropriation of bodies aroused much popular resentment.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Between 1765 and 1884, there were at least 25 documented crowd actions against American medical schools.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 1869, the body of former Queensland police officer Thomas Griffin – who had been convicted of murdering two subordinates and executed by hanging – was exhumed a week after his burial and his head removed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The body was reinterred, but after noticing that the grave had been disturbed the local sexton re-exhumed the body and discovered that it had been decapitated.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The perpetrators were never identified, but in the early 20th century it was rumoured that a local surgeon had kept the skull on display in his private collection.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In Tasmania, the bodies of William Lanne (1835–1869) and Truganini (1812–1876), considered at the time to be the last Aboriginal Tasmanians (Palawa), were both exhumed from their graves.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Lanne's head, hands and feet were removed illegally by surgeon William Crowther and members of the Royal Society of Tasmania before he was buried, and the rest of his body was stolen after his burial.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Truganini, who outlived Lanne by several years, had wished to avoid his fate and expressly asked to be cremated, but was buried anyway.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Royal Society of Tasmania exhumed her body and put it on display.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] 100 years after Truganini's death, the Palawa community finally won the rights to their bodies following many years of petitioning the Australian government, and their remains were cremated and spread in the ocean.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Indigenous Australians in mainland Australia were also subject to body snatching attempts by white Australians.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 1910, 12 indigenous bodies were stolen from their burial places along the Australian coast, where their peoples had been forced to settle after being driven away from their ancestral land.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Crowther, an 18-year-old Australian medical student seeking the favor of one of his professors.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] After obtaining the bodies, Crowther and his associates took them back to Melbourne to undergo further examination.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Project Sunshine was launched during the height of the Cold War as a series of multinational studies concerning the danger posed to humans by radioactive isotopes as a result of nuclear fallout.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Australian government became involved in the program during the mid-1950s, and began collecting body parts from citizens during autopsies, including many children, most often without their next of kin consenting or even being made aware.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] By the time the program ended in the early 1980s, the Australian government had stolen thousands upon thousands of body parts from deceased Australians to be used for research in Project Sunshine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The practice of body snatching was also common Canada, where religious customs as well as the lack of means of preservation made it hard for medical students to obtain a steady supply of fresh bodies.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In many instances the students had to resort to fairly regular body snatching.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The first medical school established in Canada was 1822 in Montreal.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Body-snatching tended to vary between English- and French-speaking students.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The French speaking students would steal bodies to pay for their schooling while the English-speaking students stole bodies for fun and were usually caught.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The students who stole the bodies for medical use would use elaborate measures to make sure the bodies could not be identified or found if a search was conducted at their residence.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Facial identifiers and scars would be removed from the body so that they could not be identified.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Students would make elaborate hiding places for the bodies such as using pulley systems to pull bodies up into chimneys or hide bodies under trap doors so that the bodies would not be found.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] When trying to find a body the robbers would be selective in that they would choose negroes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In Montreal during the winter of 1875, typhoid fever struck at a convent school.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The corpses of the victims were stolen by body snatchers before relatives arrived from the United States, causing an international scandal.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Rewards were offered which students collected to return bodies to the families.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Eventually the Anatomy Act of Quebec was amended to prevent a recurrence, effectively ending medical body snatching in Quebec.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Burial customs were regulated in China as a part of the Great Qing Legal Code in an attempt to mitigate illicit burial practices.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] These regulations criminalized the mishandling of corpses, including the removal of a corpse.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] A ghost marriage (Chinese: 冥婚; pinyin: ***mínghūn***; lit.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] 'spirit marriage') is a practice originating in China in which either one or neither of the partners in the marriage is alive.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The original purpose of ghost marriages is unclear but it has been utilized as a means of maintaining a family's honor and legacy in the event that their unwed relative is deceased.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The practice has led to the theft of female corpses in order to arrange illicit ghost marriages and relocate the body.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 2006 there were reports of a resurgence in the northern coal-mining regions of Shanxi, Hebei and Shandong.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Although the practice has long been abandoned in modern China, some superstitious families in isolated rural areas still pay very high prices for the procurement of female corpses for deceased unmarried male relatives.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] It is speculated that the very high death toll among young male miners in these areas has led more and more entrepreneurial body snatchers to steal female cadavers from graves and then resell them through the black market to families of the deceased.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 2007, a previously convicted grave robber, Song Tiantang, was arrested by Chinese authorities for murdering six women and selling their bodies as "ghost brides".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Cultural Revolution in China included a push for funeral reform which mandated the cremation of corpses.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The enforcement of this mandate has varied, but there have been instances of body snatching for the purpose of meeting state-mandated quotas for cremation funeral practices.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The act of body snatching for the purposes of meeting such quotas has become a lucrative business in China.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 2014 two local funerary practice officials in the Guangdong province of China were arrested for hiring body snatchers to acquire corpses in order to meet cremation quotas.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Red Market, also known as the organ trade, refers to the trade of human organs or other body parts with the primary purpose being transplantation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In China the illicit trading of human body parts has led to instances of body snatching for use in the Red Market.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In order to meet the demand for transplantations China authorized the use of executed prisoners' organs.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Consent of prisoners or prisoners' families, though required, has often been unverified in cases of executed prisoners' organs being harvested leading to accusations of illicit harvesting of corpses and transplantations.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In Cyprus, the former President Tassos Papadopoulos' body was stolen from his grave on 11 December 2009.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] For over 200 years, the city of Kolkata, in the north-eastern region of India, has been known to be the center of a network of bone traders who remove skeletons from graveyards in order to sell them to universities and hospitals abroad.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] During the colonial era, European doctors in the city hired thieves to dig up bodies from local cemeteries.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Despite changes in laws, a similar process is going strong today.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] According to journalist Scott Carney, historically members of the Domar caste, who traditionally performed cremations, were pressed into service processing bones; skeletons were exported from India to be used in anatomy classes worldwide.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In the 1850s, Calcutta Medical College processed 900 skeletons a year, but mostly for shipment abroad.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] A century later, a newly independent India dominated the world market for human bones.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] At their height, in the early 1980s, Calcutta's bone factories took in an estimated $1 million a year by digging the graveyards of West Bengal after the mourners had left.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 1985 the Indian government banned the export of human bones after human rights groups raised questions about how the bones were being collected and pointed towards the greater need for institutions to obtain informed consent before remains were used for medical research.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] However, the human organ trade was only forced underground.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Indian government banned the export of human remains in the mid-1980s, but body snatching is still thriving, even if secretly, in many parts of the country as a result of ineffective laws and poverty.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In Dublin, the medical schools of the 18th and 19th centuries were on a constant hunt for bodies.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Bullys' Acre or Hospital Fields at Kilmainham was a rich source of anatomical material as it was a communal burial ground and easily accessed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Soldiers attached to the nearby Royal Hospital were always on the alert for grave robbers mainly because many of their comrades were buried there.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In November 1825 a sentry captured Thomas Tuite, a known resurrectionist, in possession of five bodies.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] When searched, his pockets were found to be full of teeth–in those days a set of teeth fetched £1 (about £50 in 2011).
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Many other graveyards were targets of the medical students or those who made robbing graves their profession.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The largest cemetery in Ireland, Glasnevin Cemetery, laid out in the 18th century, had a high wall with strategically placed watch-towers as well as blood-hounds to deter body snatchers.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The first recorded case of body snatching is attributed to four medical students from Bologna in 1319.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] At this time, studying the anatomy of a human cadaver was not particularly favored once Rome fell, and it became prohibited by the Church.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] What was favored was animal dissections at this time.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Until the 15th century, it had become legal in Italy to conduct up to two dissections in public per year after the first body-snatching in the 14th century.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In The Netherlands, poorhouses were accustomed to receiving a small fee by undertakers who paid a fine for ignoring burial laws and resold the bodies (especially those with no family) to doctors.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] During the 17th century, the period of the Glorious Revolution, medicine in Great Britain and the Netherlands was at the root of body-snatching with the goal of using the corpses to be used for anatomical and physiological learning.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Among 17th-century medicine educators at universities the desire to educate the public, in particular, took place in the Dutch Republic of the Netherlands.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Dutch Province of South Holland was home to the Leiden Anatomical Theatre.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Leiden Anatomical Theatre was amongst other theatres which was centers of arts and sciences, meeting places for artists and scientists, and places of public function.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Leiden's contribution represented the model of the innovative academy and its clinical course, inaugurated in 1638, was widely seen as a center of excellence.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] After the death of Heurnius, Joannes van Horne (1621–1670) became the next caretaker for the anatomical theater.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 1974, former *de facto* President Pedro Eugenio Aramburu's body was stolen by Montoneros.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The organization had kidnapped and murdered Aramburu in 1970.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The corpse was to be held until President Isabel Perón brought back Eva Perón's body from Italy.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] It was also an act of revenge for the previous removal of Evita's body.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Once Evita's body arrived in Argentina, Montoneros gave up Aramburu's corpse and abandoned it in a street in Buenos Aires.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 1986, the hands of Juan Perón were stolen from his grave by unknown persons.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The grave of Communist leader János Kádár (1912–1989) at the Kerepesi Cemetery in Budapest was desecrated in early 2007.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] His skull has been stolen along with some of his other bones and his wife Mária Tamáska's urn.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The act was politically motivated, as a message reading "murderers and traitors cannot rest in sacred ground 1956–2006" (taken from a song by far-right rock band *Kárpátia*) was left nearby.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The two dates refer to the Hungarian Revolution of 1956 (Kádár played a major role in the suppression of the revolution), and the 2006 protests in Hungary (a scandal involving a party widely held to be the ideological successor to that of Kádár).
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] As of 2022, the bones and the perpetrators have not been found.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In 2007, the Indian police discovered a stash of hundreds of human skulls and thigh bones and arrested a gang for allegedly carrying out the practice of body snatching and indulging in bone trade.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This gang was arrested after they exhumed dozens of graves from Muslim cemeteries in Burdwan district, and smuggled the skeletons not just to medical institutions in need of cadavers across the world, but also to the Himalayan kingdom of Bhutan for use in Buddhist monasteries.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Kamal Sah was caught carrying 67 human skulls and 10 bones on a bus in Chhapra, in the state of Bihar, by fellow passengers who had noticed a jagged bone sticking out of a bag beneath his seat.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Buddhist monks in India likewise admitted that human thigh bones and skulls were used by followers of a Tibetan school of Buddhism.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] A 2009 report from The National stated that alleged bone smuggler Kamal Sah was identified by civilians in Bihar state and handed over to police with two bags of human skulls and bones.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] When questioned on the subject, the police refused to acknowledge the authorities' failure to stamp out the practice and simply claimed that the police lacked "equipment, manpower and expertise to stop this practice".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The criminal lawyer, Majid Menon, acknowledges that the dire economic conditions for vast numbers of people living in such states as Bihar, West Bengal, Jharkhand and some parts of Uttar Pradesh, have favored the practice of body snatching till date and given room for bone smugglers to flourish.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] According to estimates, 20,000–25,000 human skeletons are smuggled out of India every year through Nepal, China, and Bangladesh.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The skeletons reach markets in the US, Japan, Europe and the Middle East, mostly for medical institutions.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The price for a complete skeleton in these markets ranges from $700 to $1500 depending on the quality and size.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In India, a full skeleton costs around $350 in the open market.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Young Brothers, a Calcutta-based bone dealer, sells a human skeleton for $300.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] While the complete skeletons mostly find their way to medical laboratories mostly in the West, the assorted bones and skulls are used for religious rituals mostly in Hindu and Buddhist-dominated areas.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] As part of their tantric rituals, many tantrics drink wine in human skulls in places such as Nepal and the state of Assam in India.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] And even though to date police have been unable to unearth any irregularity in the skeleton trade, the exporter-turned-moralist, Sanker Narayan Sen, maintains that the people from the Domar caste are often responsible for body snatching and later process the procured cadavers for export.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Government of India had twice earlier banned exports, only to revoke its decision on each occasion.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] According to the Exporters Association, the CBI in 2014 had once again recently concluded its investigations and submitted a report exonerating such body snatchers and exporters.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In April 2000, the skull of antipope Benedict XIII was stolen from the ruined palace of Argillo in Sabiñán, Spain.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The thieves sent an anonymous letter to the mayor of Illueca asking for 1,000,000 ₧ (€6,000).
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The Spanish Civil Guard recovered the skull in September 2000 and found that the thieves were two local brothers who were sentenced in November 2006 to 6-month prison, substituted with €2,190.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Rare reports of body snatching continue to occur.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] One prominent case involved the removal of the remains of Gladys Hammond from Yoxall Churchyard near Lichfield in south Staffordshire.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Hammond's remains were taken by animal rights activists who were campaigning against Darley Oaks Farm, a licensed facility that bred guinea pigs for scientific research.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Hammond was the mother-in-law of one of the farm's co-owners.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The men received 12 years each and the woman received four years.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The police said the conspiracy included the removal of Hammond's remains, which were recovered by police following information given by one of the four.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] BTS sold its products to five companies, including Life Cell Corporation, of New Jersey, and Regeneration Technologies, of Florida.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] There is still a demand for corpses for transplantation surgery in the form of allografts.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Tissue gained in this way is medically unsafe and unusable.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The broadcaster Alistair Cooke's bones were removed in New York City and replaced with PVC pipe before his cremation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The director Toby Dye made a documentary titled *Body Snatcher of New York* about this case in 2010.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The 1956 science fiction film *Invasion of the Body Snatchers*, directed by Don Siegel, depicts body-snatching as a loss of personal autonomy where aliens take over the bodies of the main characters' loved ones.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This allowed for publicity of body snatching and interest in the history of its uses outside a science-fiction context.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Body snatching was portrayed in a new way of the moral consequences and surrounding effect it has on the stolen body's loved ones.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In the 1985 film *The Doctor and the Devils*, Timothy Dalton plays an anatomist who runs Edinburgh's School of Anatomy in the 19th century.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The characters in this film steal corpses after murdering locals and use them for their medical school: this is the practice of body snatching.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In the 2008 film *I Sell the Dead*, Dominic Monaghan and Larry Fessenden play two men who make a living stealing and selling corpses.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] A famous short story by Robert Louis Stevenson is "The Body Snatcher", adapted into a film starring Boris Karloff and Bela Lugosi.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This story accurately portrayed the act of body snatching and common uses in its background, taking inspiration from the Burke and Hare murders with regard to using murder to obtain the bodies for educational purposes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This story and film showed how body snatching was viewed as a dark practice with disturbing elements.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Two other works mentioning the idea of robbing a grave are The Case of Charles Dexter Ward and Herbert West–Reanimator, both by H.P.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] One of the main characters, Joseph Curwen, is a merchant and slave trader who steals corpses of well-known individuals around the world and brings them to Providence to torture them until they share their secrets.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This reflects the concept of body snatching as this character secretly removed a corpse from grave sites proving it as an unethical act.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In the 1985 novel City of Joy written by French Author and Fulbright Scholar, Dominique Lapierre, one sees how in order to pay for his daughter's wedding, the dying rickshaw driver sells his bones for science.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Hours after demise and before properly mourned, bone traders come to collect his bones.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] This provides the metaphorical practice of body snatching where a body is surrender, or stolen, and used for science such as in medical schools.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In Tess Gerritsen's 2007 novel *The Bone Garden*, set in Boston in 1830, the protagonist Norris Marshall, a talented but poor medical student, attempts to pay his college tuition by working as a "resurrectionist".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The main character Injun Joe in the popular literature work The Adventures of Tom Sawyer, takes the opportunity to murder Dr.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Robinson when he and Muff Potter are hired by him for body snatching.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] Howards novel Johannes Cabal the Necromancer, the eponymous protagonist practices body snatching.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In Charles Dickens's novel, A Tale of Two Cities, Jerry Cruncher works as a "resurrection man" stealing bodies to resurrect them in addition to his work as a porter and messenger at Tellson's Bank.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] In popular culture, music referencing the act of body snatching includes the Pet Shop Boys' song "The Resurrectionist" which appeared as a bonus track on "I'm with Stupid", the first single from their 2006 album *Fundamental*.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The track is inspired by the book *The Italian Boy: Murder and Grave-Robbery in 1830s London* by Sarah Wise.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] (See London Burkers.) The 9th track of leATHERMØUTH's album *XØ*, titled "Bodysnatchers 4 Ever", describes a man and his lover taking fresh bodies, which they use in order to live forever.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The second track on Radiohead's 2007 album *In Rainbows* is titled "Bodysnatchers".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The debut single of experimental band Ralph and the Hexagons, "My Weekend Plans", is about an attempted act of body snatching, although this is referred to as grave robbing throughout the song.
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] The 6th track of Creature Feature's album "It Was A Dark And Stormy Night..." is titled "Grave Robber At Large".
[src:alexis-st-martin/body-snatching] It is about a stereotypical early 19th century body snatcher, featuring the hook "Death is my business, and business is good!".
[src:alexis-st-martin/cathartic] In medicine, a **cathartic** is a substance that *accelerates* defecation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/cathartic] This is similar to a laxative, which is a substance that *eases* defecation, usually by softening feces.
[src:alexis-st-martin/cathartic] It is possible for a substance to be both a laxative and a cathartic.
[src:alexis-st-martin/cathartic] However, agents such as psyllium seed husks increase the bulk of the feces.
[src:alexis-st-martin/cathartic] Cathartics such as sorbitol, magnesium citrate, magnesium sulfate, or sodium sulfate were previously used as a form of gastrointestinal decontamination following poisoning via ingestion.
[src:alexis-st-martin/cathartic] They are no longer routinely recommended for poisonings.
[src:alexis-st-martin/cathartic] High-dose cathartics may be an effective means of ridding the lower gastrointestinal tract of toxins; however, they carry a risk of electrolyte imbalances and dehydration.
[src:alexis-st-martin/cathartic] Catharsis can be an effect of pesticide poisonings, such as with elemental sulfur.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] A **coureur des bois** (French: [kuʁœʁ de bwɑ]; lit.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] 'runner of the woods') or **coureur de bois** (French: [kuʁœʁ də bwɑ]; pl.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] **coureurs de(s) bois**) were independent entrepreneurial French Canadian traders who travelled in New France and the interior of North America, usually to trade with First Nations peoples by exchanging various European items for furs.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Sometimes they operated in competition with the larger and licensed *voyageurs*.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Some coureurs des bois learned the trades and practices of the indigenous peoples, and even went into business with them.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] These expeditions were part of the beginning of the fur trade in the North American interior.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Initially they traded for beaver coats and furs.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] However, as the market grew, *coureurs de bois* were trapping and trading prime beavers whose skins were to be felted in Europe.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] While French settlers had lived and traded alongside Indigenous people since the earliest days of New France, coureurs des bois reached their apex during the second half of the 17th century.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] After 1681, the independent coureur des bois was gradually replaced by state-sponsored voyageurs, who were workers associated with licensed fur traders.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Coureurs des bois lost their importance in the fur trade by the early 18th century.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Yet, even while their numbers were dwindling, the coureur des bois developed as a symbol of the colony, creating a lasting myth that would continue to define New France for centuries.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Shortly after founding a permanent settlement at Quebec City in 1608, Samuel de Champlain sought to ally himself with the local native peoples or First Nations.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] He decided to send French boys to live among them to learn their languages in order to serve as interpreters, in the hope of persuading the natives to trade with the French rather than with the Dutch, who were active along the Hudson River and Atlantic coast.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The boys learned native languages, customs, and skills, and tended to assimilate quickly to their new environments.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] A year after leaving Étienne Brûlé in 1610, with a Huron tribe, Champlain visited him and was surprised to find the young man attired completely in native clothing and able to converse fluently in the Huron language.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Early explorers such as Brûlé educated the French colonists on the complex trading networks of the natives, served as interpreters, and encouraged the burgeoning fur trade.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Between 1610 and 1629, dozens of Frenchmen spent months at a time living among the natives.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Over time, these early explorers and interpreters played an increasingly active role in the fur trade, paving the way for the emergence of the coureurs des bois proper in the mid-17th century.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The term "coureur des bois" is most strongly associated with those who engaged in the fur trade in ways that were considered to be outside of the mainstream.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Early in the North American fur trade era, this term was applied to men who circumvented the normal channels by going deeper into the wilderness to trade.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Traditionally, the government of New France preferred to let the natives supply furs directly to French merchants, and discouraged French settlers from venturing outside the Saint Lawrence valley.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] By the mid-17th century, Montreal had emerged as the center of the fur trade, hosting a yearly fair in August where natives exchanged their pelts for European goods.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] While coureurs des bois never entirely disappeared, they were heavily discouraged by French colonial officials.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] In 1649, the new governor Louis d'Ailleboust permitted Frenchmen familiar with the wilderness to visit Huron Country to encourage and escort Hurons to Montreal to participate in the trade.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] While this did not legally sanction coureurs des bois to trade independently with the natives, some historians consider d'Ailleboust's encouragement of independent traders to mark the official emergence of the coureurs des bois.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] In the 1660s, several factors resulted in a sudden spike in the number of coureurs des bois.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] First, the population of New France markedly increased during the late 17th century, as the colony experienced a boom in immigration between 1667–84.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Of the new *engagés* (indentured male servants), discharged soldiers, and youthful immigrants from squalid, class-bound Europe arriving in great numbers in the colony, many chose freedom in the life of the coureur des bois.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Furthermore, renewed peaceful relations with the Iroquois in 1667 made travelling into the interior of Canada much less perilous for the French colonists.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The companies that had been monopolizing and regulating the fur trade since 1645, the *Cent Associés* and the *Communautés des Habitants*, went bankrupt after the Iroquois war.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The *Compagnie des Indes occidentales*, which replaced them, was much less restrictive of internal trade, allowing independent merchants to become more numerous.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Finally, a sudden fall in the price of beaver on the European markets in 1664 caused more traders to travel to the *"pays d'en haut"*, or upper country (the area around the Great Lakes), in search of cheaper pelts.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] During the mid-1660s, therefore, becoming a coureur des bois became both more feasible and profitable.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] This sudden growth alarmed many colonial officials.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] In 1680, the intendant Duchesneau estimated there were eight hundred coureurs des bois, or about 40% of the adult male population.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Reports like that were wildly exaggerated: in reality, even at their zenith coureurs des bois remained a very small percentage of the population of New France.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] In 1681, to curb the unregulated business of independent traders and their burgeoning profits, French minister of marine Jean-Baptiste Colbert created a system of licences for fur traders, known as *congés*.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Initially, this system granted 25 annual licences to merchants travelling inland.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The recipients of these licences came to be known as "voyageurs" (travellers), who canoed and portaged fur trade goods in the employ of a licensed fur trader or fur trading company.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The congé system, therefore, created the voyageur, the legal and respectable counterpart to the coureur des bois.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Under the voyageurs, the fur trade began to favour a more organized business model of the times, including monopolistic ownership and hired labour.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] From 1681 onwards, therefore, the voyageurs began to eclipse the coureurs des bois, although coureurs des bois continued to trade without licences for several decades.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Following the implementation of the congé system, the number of coureurs des bois dwindled, as did their influence within the colony.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] A successful coureur des bois had to possess many skills, including those of businessman and expert canoeist.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] To survive in the Canadian wilderness, coureurs des bois also had to be competent in a range of activities including fishing, snowshoeing and hunting.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The life was physically arduous and succeeding as a coureur was extremely difficult.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] But the hope of making a profit motivated many, while the promise of adventure and freedom was enough to convince others to become coureurs.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Because of the lack of roads and the necessity to transport heavy goods and furs, fur trade in the interior of the continent depended on men conducting long-distance transportation by canoe of fur trade goods, and returning with pelts.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Early travel was dangerous and the *coureurs des bois*, who traded in uncharted territory, had a high mortality rate.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Typically, they left Montreal in the spring, as soon as the rivers and lakes were clear of ice (usually May), their canoes loaded with supplies and goods for trading.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The course west to the richest beaver lands usually went by way of the Ottawa and Mattawa rivers; it required numerous overland portages.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Alternatively, some canoes proceeded by way of the upper St.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Lawrence River and the lakes, passing by Detroit on the way to Michilimackinac or Green Bay.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] This route had fewer portages, but in times of war, it was more exposed to Iroquois attacks.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The powerful Five Nations of the Confederacy had territory along the Great Lakes and sought to control their hunting grounds.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Such trading journeys often lasted for months and covered thousands of kilometers, with the *coureurs des bois* sometimes paddling twelve hours a day.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Packing a canoe for such a trip was often arduous, as more than thirty articles were considered essential for a coureur des bois's survival and business.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The business of a *coureur des bois* required close contact with Indigenous peoples.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Native peoples were essential because they trapped the fur-bearing animals (especially beaver) and prepared the skins.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Relations between *coureurs* and natives were not always peaceful, and could sometimes become violent.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] In general, trade was made much easier by the two groups maintaining friendly relations.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Trade was often accompanied by reciprocal gift-giving; among the Algonquin and others, exchanging gifts was customary practice to maintain alliances.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Pierre-Esprit Radisson and his companions, for instance, "struck agreeable relations with Natives inland by giving European goods as gifts".
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Furthermore, relations between the coureur de bois and the natives often included a cultural dimension; marriage *à la façon du pays* (following local custom) was common between native women and coureurs des bois, and later between native women and voyageurs.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] These unions were of benefit to both sides, and in later years, winter partners of major trading companies also took native wives.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] As wives, indigenous women played a key role as translators, guides and mediators—becoming "women between".
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] For one thing, Algonquin communities typically had far more women than men, likely as a result of warfare .
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The remaining marriages between Algonquins tended to be polygamous, with one husband marrying two or more women.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Sexual relationships with coureurs des bois therefore offered native women an alternative to polygamy in a society with few available men.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] To French military commanders, who were often also directly involved in the fur trade, such marriages were beneficial in that they improved relations between the French and the natives.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Native leaders also encouraged such unions, particularly when the couple formed lasting, permanent bonds.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Jesuits and some upper-level colonial officials viewed these relationships with disdain and disgust.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] French officials preferred coureurs des bois and voyageurs to settle around Quebec City and Montreal.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] They considered the lasting relationships with native women to be further proof of the lawlessness and perversion of the coureurs des bois.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The role and importance of the coureurs des bois have been exaggerated over the course of history.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] This figure has achieved mythological status, leading to many false accounts, and to the coureurs des bois being assimilated with "*Canadiens*" (French Canadians).
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The mythmaking followed two paths; initially, people in France judged the colonies according to the fears and apprehensions which they had of the Ancien Régime.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] If order and discipline were proving difficult to maintain in continental Europe, it seemed impossible that the colonies would fare any better, and it was presumed things would become even worse.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The myth of the coureurs des bois as representative of the Canadians was stimulated by the writings of 18th-century Jesuit priest F-X.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Charlevoix and the 19th-century American historian Francis Parkman; their historical accounts are classified as belonging to popular rather than academic history.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Charlevoix was particularly influential in his writings, because he was a trusted source of information, as he was a Jesuit priest who had journeyed in Canada.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] But his "historical" work has been criticized by historians for being too "light" and for relying too heavily on other authors' material (i.e. plagiarizing), rather than his own first-hand account.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Critics of Charlevoix have also noted that in his account, he confuses different periods of time, and therefore does not differentiate between voyageurs and coureurs des bois, misrepresenting the importance of the latter in terms of number and proportion in terms on influence on trading.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] But Charlevoix was influential; his work was often cited by other authors, which further propagated the myth of the Canadian as a coureur des bois.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Finally, romans du terroir (rural novels) also added to the myth of the coureurs des bois by featuring them out of proportion to their number and influence.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The coureurs des bois were portrayed in such works as extremely virile, free-spirited and of untameable natures, ideal protagonists in the romanticized novels of important 19th-century writers such as Chateaubriand, Jules Verne and Fenimore Cooper.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The coureurs des bois were known for their trapping abilities by outside parties but French Canadians knew these men as being looked upon without favour.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The coureur des bois lived outside of the typical confines of society and had to adapt to the expectations of the Indigenous peoples around them.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] They did this by adopting the Indigenous people's ritual practices and marrying Indigenous women.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] French Canadians associated the coureur des bois with being ungovernable and fearless men.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The biggest problem with the coureur des bois was their interference with the missionary effort of the French Canadians.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] They denounced the French priests and missionaries and undermined their evangelistic efforts by supplying the Indigenous peoples with liquor.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The coureur des bois refusal to submit to the will of the missionaries made them an enemy.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] This resulted in the coureur des bois being labelled as unruly and a threat to colonial survival.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The coureurs des bois were renowned for their ability to trap animals for the fur trade but their overall reputation was negative for French Canadians.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The coureurs des bois are often confused with voyagers however the two groups had very different reputations.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The coureurs des bois were considered outlaws because of their lack of licences to participate in the fur trade.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The requirement of licences to participate in trapping and trading furs limited the types of people who could participate in the lucrative trade.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Trapping and trading without one of the required licences was a legally punishable offence.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The coureurs des bois were seen by the French government and French citizens as problematic because they did not abide by the licensing laws.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Additionally, the coureurs des bois were seen more frequently as explorers than their voyager counterparts.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The voyager's ties to fur companies dictated how and where they trapped, whereas the coureur des bois were free to explore and trap in any place they could find.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The coureur des bois freedom and intimate ties to the Indigenous peoples resulted in many French people viewing them as only a step above Native American men.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Most coureurs des bois were primarily or solely fur-trade entrepreneurs and not individually well known.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The most prominent coureurs des bois were also explorers and gained fame as such.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The 1910 Victor Herbert operetta *Naughty Marietta* featured the male-chorus marching song *Tramp Tramp Tramp (Along the Highway)*, which included the words, "Blazing trails along the byway / Couriers de Bois are we" [sic].
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Pasquinel was portrayed in the miniseries by American TV actor Robert Conrad.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The fictional character of Pasquinel was loosely based on the lives of French-speaking fur traders Jacques La Ramee and Ceran St.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] The 2016 television series *Frontier* chronicles the North American fur trade in late 1700s Canada, and follows Declan Harp, a part-Irish, part-Cree outlaw who is campaigning to breach the Hudson's Bay Company's monopoly on the fur trade in Canada.
[src:alexis-st-martin/coureur-des-bois] Several fictional coureurs des bois are featured in this realistic action-drama filmed mostly on location in Newfoundland and Labrador, Nova Scotia, and Ontario, Canada.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In the human digestive system, food enters the mouth and mechanical digestion of the food starts by the action of mastication (chewing), a form of mechanical digestion, and the wetting contact of saliva.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Saliva, a liquid secreted by the salivary glands, contains salivary amylase, an enzyme which starts the digestion of starch in the food.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The saliva also contains mucus, which lubricates the food; the electrolyte hydrogencarbonate (HCO−3), which provides the ideal conditions of pH for amylase to work; and other electrolytes (Na+, K+, Cl−).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] About 30% of starch is hydrolyzed into disaccharide in the oral cavity (mouth).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] After undergoing mastication and starch digestion, the food will be in the form of a small, round slurry mass called a bolus.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] It will then travel down the esophagus and into the stomach by the action of peristalsis.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Gastric juice in the stomach starts protein digestion.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Gastric juice mainly contains hydrochloric acid and pepsin.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In infants and toddlers, gastric juice also contains rennin to digest milk proteins.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] As the first two chemicals may damage the stomach wall, mucus and bicarbonates are secreted by the stomach.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] They provide a slimy layer that acts as a shield against the damaging effects of chemicals like concentrated hydrochloric acid while also aiding lubrication.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Hydrochloric acid provides acidic pH for pepsin.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] At the same time protein digestion is occurring, mechanical mixing occurs by peristalsis, which is waves of muscular contractions that move along the stomach wall.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This allows the mass of food to further mix with the digestive enzymes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Pepsin breaks down proteins into peptides or proteoses, which are further broken down into dipeptides and amino acids by enzymes in the small intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Studies suggest that increasing the number of chews per bite increases relevant gut hormones and may decrease self-reported hunger and food intake.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] When the pyloric sphincter valve opens, partially digested food (chyme) enters the duodenum where it mixes with digestive enzymes from the pancreas and bile juice from the liver and then passes through the small intestine, in which digestion continues.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] When the chyme is fully digested, it is passed through the liver before being absorbed into the blood.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] 95% of nutrient absorption occurs in the small intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Water and minerals are reabsorbed back into the blood in the colon (large intestine) where the pH is slightly acidic (about 5.6 ~ 6.9).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Some vitamins, such as biotin and vitamin K (K2MK7) produced by bacteria in the colon are also absorbed into the blood in the colon.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Absorption of water, simple sugar and alcohol also takes place in stomach.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Waste material (feces) is eliminated from the rectum during defecation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] There is a fundamental distinction between internal and external digestion.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] External digestion developed earlier in evolutionary history, and most fungi still rely on it.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In this process, enzymes are secreted into the environment surrounding the organism, where they break down an organic material, and some of the products diffuse back to the organism.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Animals have a tube (gastrointestinal tract) in which internal digestion occurs, which is more efficient because more of the broken down products can be captured, and the internal chemical environment can be more efficiently controlled.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Some organisms, including nearly all spiders, secrete biotoxins and digestive chemicals (e.g., enzymes) into the extracellular environment prior to ingestion of the consequent "soup".
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In others, once potential nutrients or food is inside the organism, digestion can be conducted to a vesicle or a sac-like structure, through a tube, or through several specialized organs aimed at making the absorption of nutrients more efficient.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Bacteria use several systems to obtain nutrients from other organisms in the environments.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In a channel transport system, several proteins form a contiguous channel traversing the inner and outer membranes of the bacteria.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] It is a simple system, which consists of only three protein subunits: the ABC protein, membrane fusion protein (MFP), and outer membrane protein.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This secretion system transports various chemical species, from ions, drugs, to proteins of various sizes (20–900 kDa).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The chemical species secreted vary in size from the small *Escherichia coli* peptide colicin V, (10 kDa) to the *Pseudomonas fluorescens* cell adhesion protein LapA of 900 kDa.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] A type III secretion system means that a molecular syringe is used through which a bacterium (e.g. certain types of *Salmonella*, *Shigella*, *Yersinia*) can inject nutrients into protist cells.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] One such mechanism was first discovered in *Y. pestis* and showed that toxins could be injected directly from the bacterial cytoplasm into the cytoplasm of its host's cells rather than be secreted into the extracellular medium.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The conjugation machinery of some bacteria (and archaeal flagella) is capable of transporting both DNA and proteins.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] It was discovered in *Agrobacterium tumefaciens*, which uses this system to introduce the Ti plasmid and proteins into the host, which develops the crown gall (tumor).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The VirB complex of *Agrobacterium tumefaciens* is the prototypic system.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In the nitrogen-fixing *Rhizobia*, conjugative elements naturally engage in inter-kingdom conjugation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Such elements as the *Agrobacterium* Ti or Ri plasmids contain elements that can transfer to plant cells.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Transferred genes enter the plant cell nucleus and effectively transform the plant cells into factories for the production of opines, which the bacteria use as carbon and energy sources.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Infected plant cells form crown gall or root tumors.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The Ti and Ri plasmids are thus endosymbionts of the bacteria, which are in turn endosymbionts (or parasites) of the infected plant.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The Ti and Ri plasmids are themselves conjugative.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Ti and Ri transfer between bacteria uses an independent system (the *tra*, or transfer, operon) from that for inter-kingdom transfer (the *vir*, or virulence, operon).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Such transfer creates virulent strains from previously avirulent *Agrobacteria*.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In addition to the use of the multiprotein complexes listed above, gram-negative bacteria possess another method for release of material: the formation of outer membrane vesicles.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Portions of the outer membrane pinch off, forming spherical structures made of a lipid bilayer enclosing periplasmic materials.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Vesicles from a number of bacterial species have been found to contain virulence factors, some have immunomodulatory effects, and some can directly adhere to and intoxicate host cells.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] While release of vesicles has been demonstrated as a general response to stress conditions, the process of loading cargo proteins seems to be selective.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The gastrovascular cavity functions as a stomach in both digestion and the distribution of nutrients to all parts of the body.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Extracellular digestion takes place within this central cavity, which is lined with the gastrodermis, the internal layer of epithelium.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This cavity has only one opening to the outside that functions as both a mouth and an anus: waste and undigested matter is excreted through the mouth/anus, which can be described as an incomplete gut.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] A phagosome is a vacuole formed around a particle absorbed by phagocytosis.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The vacuole is formed by the fusion of the cell membrane around the particle.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] A phagosome is a cellular compartment in which pathogenic microorganisms can be killed and digested.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Phagosomes fuse with lysosomes in their maturation process, forming phagolysosomes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In humans, *Entamoeba histolytica* can phagocytose red blood cells.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] To aid in the digestion of their food, animals evolved organs such as beaks, tongues, radulae, teeth, crops, gizzards, and others.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Birds have bony beaks that are specialised according to the bird's ecological niche.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] For example, macaws primarily eat seeds, nuts, and fruit, using their beaks to open even the toughest seed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] First they scratch a thin line with the sharp point of the beak, then they shear the seed open with the sides of the beak.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The mouth of the squid is equipped with a sharp horny beak mainly made of cross-linked proteins.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] It is used to kill and tear prey into manageable pieces.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The beak is very robust, but does not contain any minerals, unlike the teeth and jaws of many other organisms, including marine species.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The beak is the only indigestible part of the squid.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The **tongue** is skeletal muscle on the floor of the mouth of most vertebrates, that manipulates food for chewing (mastication) and swallowing (deglutition).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] It is sensitive and kept moist by saliva.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The underside of the tongue is covered with a smooth mucous membrane.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The tongue also has a touch sense for locating and positioning food particles that require further chewing.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The tongue is used to roll food particles into a bolus before being transported down the esophagus through peristalsis.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The sublingual region underneath the front of the tongue is a location where the oral mucosa is very thin, and underlain by a plexus of veins.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This is an ideal location for introducing certain medications to the body.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The sublingual route takes advantage of the highly vascular quality of the oral cavity, and allows for the speedy application of medication into the cardiovascular system, bypassing the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Teeth (singular tooth) are small whitish structures found in the jaws (or mouths) of many vertebrates that are used to tear, scrape, milk and chew food.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Teeth are not made of bone, but rather of tissues of varying density and hardness, such as enamel, dentine and cementum.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Human teeth have a blood and nerve supply which enables proprioception.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This is the ability of sensation when chewing, for example if we were to bite into something too hard for our teeth, such as a chipped plate mixed in food, our teeth send a message to our brain and we realise that it cannot be chewed, so we stop trying.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The shapes, sizes and numbers of types of animals' teeth are related to their diets.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] For example, herbivores have a number of molars which are used to grind plant matter, which is difficult to digest.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Carnivores have canine teeth which are used to kill and tear meat.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] A crop, or croup, is a thin-walled expanded portion of the alimentary tract used for the storage of food prior to digestion.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In some birds it is an expanded, muscular pouch near the gullet or throat.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In adult doves and pigeons, the crop can produce crop milk to feed newly hatched birds.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Certain insects may have a crop or enlarged esophagus.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Herbivores have evolved cecums (or an abomasum in the case of ruminants).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Ruminants have a fore-stomach with four chambers.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] These are the rumen, reticulum, omasum, and abomasum.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In the first two chambers, the rumen and the reticulum, the food is mixed with saliva and separates into layers of solid and liquid material.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Solids clump together to form the cud (or bolus).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The cud is then regurgitated, chewed slowly to completely mix it with saliva and to break down the particle size.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Fibre, especially cellulose and hemi-cellulose, is primarily broken down into the volatile fatty acids, acetic acid, propionic acid and butyric acid in these chambers (the reticulo-rumen) by microbes: (bacteria, protozoa, and fungi).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In the omasum, water and many of the inorganic mineral elements are absorbed into the blood stream.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The abomasum is the fourth and final stomach compartment in ruminants.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] It is a close equivalent of a monogastric stomach (e.g., those in humans or pigs), and digesta is processed here in much the same way.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] It serves primarily as a site for acid hydrolysis of microbial and dietary protein, preparing these protein sources for further digestion and absorption in the small intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Digesta is finally moved into the small intestine, where the digestion and absorption of nutrients occurs.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Microbes produced in the reticulo-rumen are also digested in the small intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Regurgitation has been mentioned above under abomasum and crop, referring to crop milk, a secretion from the lining of the crop of pigeons and doves with which the parents feed their young by regurgitation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Many sharks have the ability to turn their stomachs inside out and evert it out of their mouths in order to get rid of unwanted contents (perhaps developed as a way to reduce exposure to toxins).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Other animals, such as rabbits and rodents, produce cecotropes to re-digest food, especially in the case of roughage.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Capybaras, rabbits, hamsters, and other related species do not have a complex digestive system as ruminants.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] They instead extract more nutrition by giving their food a second pass through the gut.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Soft cecotropes of partially digested food are excreted and generally consumed immediately.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] They also produce normal droppings, which are not eaten.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Young elephants, pandas, koalas, and hippos eat the faeces of their mother, probably to obtain the bacteria required to properly digest vegetation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] When they are born, their intestines do not contain these bacteria (they are completely sterile).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Without them, they would be unable to get any nutritional value from many plant components.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] An earthworm's digestive system consists of a mouth, pharynx, esophagus, crop, gizzard, and intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The mouth is surrounded by strong lips, which act like a hand to grab pieces of dead grass, leaves, and weeds, with bits of soil to help chew.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The lips break the food down into smaller pieces.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In the pharynx, the food is lubricated by mucus secretions for easier passage.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The esophagus adds calcium carbonate to neutralize the acids formed by food matter decay.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Temporary storage occurs in the crop where food and calcium carbonate are mixed.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The powerful muscles of the gizzard churn and mix the mass of food and dirt.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] When the churning is complete, the glands in the walls of the gizzard add enzymes to the thick paste, which helps chemically breakdown the organic matter.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] By peristalsis, the mixture is sent to the intestine where friendly bacteria continue chemical breakdown.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This releases carbohydrates, protein, fat, and various vitamins and minerals for absorption into the body.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In most vertebrates, digestion is a multistage process in the digestive system, starting from ingestion of raw materials, most often other organisms.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Ingestion usually involves some type of mechanical and chemical processing.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Egestion (Excretion): Removal of undigested materials from the digestive tract through defecation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Underlying the process is muscle movement throughout the system through swallowing and peristalsis.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Each step in digestion requires energy, and thus imposes an "overhead charge" on the energy made available from absorbed substances.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Differences in that overhead cost are important influences on lifestyle, behavior, and even physical structures.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Examples may be seen in humans, who differ considerably from other hominids (lack of hair, smaller jaws and musculature, different dentition, length of intestines, cooking, etc.).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The major part of digestion takes place in the small intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The large intestine primarily serves as a site for fermentation of indigestible matter by gut bacteria and for resorption of water from digests before excretion.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In mammals, preparation for digestion begins with the cephalic phase in which saliva is produced in the mouth and digestive enzymes are produced in the stomach.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Mechanical and chemical digestion begin in the mouth where food is chewed, and mixed with saliva to begin enzymatic processing of starches.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The stomach continues to break food down mechanically and chemically through churning and mixing with both acids and enzymes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Absorption occurs in the stomach and gastrointestinal tract, and the process finishes with defecation.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The human gastrointestinal tract is around 9 metres (30 feet) long.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Food digestion physiology varies between individuals and upon other factors such as the characteristics of the food and size of the meal, and the process of digestion normally takes between 24 and 72 hours.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Digestion begins in the mouth with the secretion of saliva and its digestive enzymes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Food is formed into a bolus by the mechanical mastication and swallowed into the esophagus from where it enters the stomach through the action of peristalsis.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Gastric juice contains hydrochloric acid and pepsin two chemicals that could damage the stomach lining, but mucus and bicarbonates are secreted to protect against this.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In the stomach further release of enzymes break down the food further and this is combined with the churning action of the stomach.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Mainly proteins are digested in stomach.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The partially digested food enters the duodenum as a thick semi-liquid chyme.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In the small intestine, the larger part of digestion takes place and this is helped by the secretions of bile, pancreatic juice and intestinal juice.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The intestinal walls are lined with villi, and their epithelial cells are covered with numerous microvilli to improve the absorption of nutrients by increasing the surface area of the intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Bile helps in emulsification of fats and also activates lipases.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In the large intestine, the passage of food is slower to enable fermentation by the gut flora to take place.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Here, water is absorbed and waste material stored as feces to be removed by defecation via the anal canal and anus.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Different phases of digestion take place including: the cephalic phase, gastric phase, and intestinal phase.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The cephalic phase occurs at the sight, thought and smell of food, which stimulate the cerebral cortex.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Taste and smell stimuli are sent to the hypothalamus and medulla oblongata.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] After this it is routed through the vagus nerve and release of acetylcholine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Gastric secretion at this phase rises to 40% of maximum rate.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Acidity in the stomach is not buffered by food at this point and thus acts to inhibit parietal (secretes acid) and G cell (secretes gastrin) activity via D cell secretion of somatostatin.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] It is stimulated by distension of the stomach, presence of food in stomach and decrease in pH.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Distention activates long and myenteric reflexes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This activates the release of acetylcholine, which stimulates the release of more gastric juices.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] As protein enters the stomach, it binds to hydrogen ions, which raises the pH of the stomach.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Inhibition of gastrin and gastric acid secretion is lifted.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This triggers G cells to release gastrin, which in turn stimulates parietal cells to secrete gastric acid.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Gastric acid is about 0.5% hydrochloric acid, which lowers the pH to the desired pH of 1–3.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Acid release is also triggered by acetylcholine and histamine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The intestinal phase has two parts, the excitatory and the inhibitory.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Partially digested food fills the duodenum.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This triggers intestinal gastrin to be released.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Enterogastric reflex inhibits vagal nuclei, activating sympathetic fibers causing the pyloric sphincter to tighten to prevent more food from entering, and inhibits local reflexes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Protein digestion occurs in the stomach and duodenum in which three main enzymes, pepsin secreted by the stomach and trypsin and chymotrypsin secreted by the pancreas, break down food proteins into polypeptides that are then broken down by various exopeptidases and dipeptidases into amino acids.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The digestive enzymes however are mostly secreted as their inactive precursors, the zymogens.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] For example, trypsin is secreted by pancreas in the form of trypsinogen, which is activated in the duodenum by enterokinase to form trypsin.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Trypsin then cleaves proteins to smaller polypeptides.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Digestion of some fats can begin in the mouth where lingual lipase breaks down some short chain lipids into diglycerides.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] However fats are mainly digested in the small intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The presence of fat in the small intestine produces hormones that stimulate the release of pancreatic lipase from the pancreas and bile from the liver which helps in the emulsification of fats for absorption of fatty acids.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Complete digestion of one molecule of fat (a triglyceride) results a mixture of fatty acids, mono- and di-glycerides, but no glycerol.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In humans, dietary starches are composed of glucose units arranged in long chains called amylose, a polysaccharide.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] During digestion, bonds between glucose molecules are broken by salivary and pancreatic amylase, resulting in progressively smaller chains of glucose.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This results in simple sugars glucose and maltose (2 glucose molecules) that can be absorbed by the small intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Lactase is an enzyme that breaks down the disaccharide lactose to its component parts, glucose and galactose.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Glucose and galactose can be absorbed by the small intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Approximately 65 percent of the adult population produce only small amounts of lactase and are unable to eat unfermented milk-based foods.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This is commonly known as lactose intolerance.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Lactose intolerance varies widely by genetic heritage; more than 90 percent of peoples of east Asian descent are lactose intolerant, in contrast to about 5 percent of people of northern European descent.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Sucrase is an enzyme that breaks down the disaccharide sucrose, commonly known as table sugar, cane sugar, or beet sugar.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Sucrose digestion yields the sugars fructose and glucose which are readily absorbed by the small intestine.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] DNA and RNA are broken down into mononucleotides by the nucleases deoxyribonuclease (DNase), and ribonuclease (RNase) from the pancreas.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Some nutrients are complex molecules (for example vitamin B12) which would be destroyed if they were broken down into their functional groups.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] To digest vitamin B12 non-destructively, haptocorrin in saliva strongly binds and protects the B12 molecules from stomach acid as they enter the stomach and are cleaved from their protein complexes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] After the B12-haptocorrin complexes pass from the stomach via the pylorus to the duodenum, pancreatic proteases cleave haptocorrin from the B12 molecules which rebind to intrinsic factor (IF).
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] These B12-IF complexes travel to the ileum portion of the small intestine where cubilin receptors enable assimilation and circulation of B12-IF complexes in the blood.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] There are at least five hormones that aid and regulate the digestive system in mammals.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] There are variations across the vertebrates, as for instance in birds.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Arrangements are complex and additional details are regularly discovered.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Connections to metabolic control (largely the glucose-insulin system) have been uncovered.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Digestion is a complex process controlled by several factors. pH plays a crucial role in a normally functioning digestive tract.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In the mouth, pharynx and esophagus, pH is typically about 6.8, very weakly acidic.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Saliva controls pH in this region of the digestive tract.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Salivary amylase is contained in saliva and starts the breakdown of carbohydrates into monosaccharides.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] Most digestive enzymes are sensitive to pH and will denature in a high or low pH environment.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The stomach's high acidity inhibits the breakdown of carbohydrates within it.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] This acidity confers two benefits: it denatures proteins for further digestion in the small intestines, and provides non-specific immunity, damaging or eliminating various pathogens.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] In the small intestines, the duodenum provides critical pH balancing to activate digestive enzymes.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The liver secretes bile into the duodenum to neutralize the acidic conditions from the stomach, and the pancreatic duct empties into the duodenum, adding bicarbonate to neutralize the acidic chyme, thus creating a neutral environment.
[src:alexis-st-martin/digestion] The mucosal tissue of the small intestines is alkaline with a pH of about 8.5.
[src:alexis-st-martin/dit-name] The ***dit* name** (French: *nom-dit* [nɔ̃ di]) is a mostly French-Canadian custom by which families often adopted an alternative surname.
[src:alexis-st-martin/dit-name] They are also used in France, Jersey, Italy, Scotland, and areas of the United States with a French cultural background, such as Louisiana and New Hampshire.
[src:alexis-st-martin/dit-name] The practice of giving such names was common in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, and though some people later simplified their surnames, some of them are still used in the twenty-first century.
[src:alexis-st-martin/dit-name] The *dit* name poses challenges for genealogists confronted with different surnames in different documents, particularly if they are not familiar with the custom.
[src:alexis-st-martin/dit-name] A family's *dit* name often derived from a personal attribute (Leblond, Leblanc, Leroux), place of origin (St-Onge, Coderre, LeBreton), or profession (Chartier, Meunier, Vanier).
[src:alexis-st-martin/dit-name] For example, an immigrant to New France from Paris might receive the *dit* name *Parisien*, and a person who worked as a blacksmith might receive the dit name *Lefebvre*.
[src:alexis-st-martin/dit-name] A large person could be "Tiny" or Petit.
[src:alexis-st-martin/dit-name] The custom originated in the military, where those with the same name adopted *noms de guerre* to distinguish themselves.
[src:alexis-st-martin/dit-name] Children often adopted the *dit* name, sometimes dropping the original family name.
[src:alexis-st-martin/dit-name] Sometimes some of the children chose to take only the family name and others only the *dit* name.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] An anal fistula connects the anal canal to the perianal skin.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] An anovaginal or rectovaginal fistula is a hole joining the anus or rectum to the vagina.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] A colovaginal fistula joins the space in the colon to that in the vagina.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] A urinary tract fistula is an abnormal opening in the urinary tract or an abnormal connection between the urinary tract and another organ.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] An abnormal communication (i.e. hole or tube) between the bladder and the uterus is called a vesicouterine fistula, while if it is between the bladder and the vagina it is known as a vesicovaginal fistula, and if between the urethra and the vagina: a urethrovaginal fistula.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] When occurring between two parts of the intestine, it is known as an enteroenteral fistula, between the small intestine and the skin it is known as an enterocutaneous fistula, and between the colon and the skin as a colocutaneous fistula.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] A fistula can result from an infection, inflammation, injury or surgery.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Many result from complications during childbirth.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Sometimes a fistula is deliberately surgically created as part of a treatment, for example in the case of an arteriovenous fistula for hemodialysis.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] The treatment for a fistula varies depending on the type, cause, and severity of the fistula, but often involves surgical intervention combined with antibiotic therapy.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] In some cases the fistula is temporarily covered using a fibrin glue or plug.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] A catheter may be required to drain a fistula.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Globally, every year between 50,000 and 100,000 women are affected by one or more fistulas relating to childbirth.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Typically they are vaginal fistulas, between either the bowel or bladder and the vaginal canal, but uterine and bowel fistulas also occur.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] In botany, the term is most common in its adjectival forms, where it is used in binomial names to refer to a species that is distinguished by one or more hollow or tubular structures.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] *Monarda fistulosa*, for example, has tubular flowers.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] The term was first used in the 14th century.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] A fistula is an abnormal connection between vessels or organs that do not usually connect.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] It can be due to a disease or trauma, or purposely surgically created.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Although most fistulas are in forms of a tube, some can also have multiple branches.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Types of fistula can be described by their location.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Anal fistulas connect between the epithelialized surface of the anal canal and the perianal skin.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Anovaginal or rectovaginal fistulas occur when a hole develops between the anus or rectum and the vagina.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Colovaginal fistulas occur between the colon and the vagina.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] When occurring between two parts of the intestine, it is known as an enteroenteral fistula, between the small intestine and the skin as an enterocutaneous fistula, and between the small intestine and the colon as a colocutaneous fistula.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] The following list is sorted by the International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Treatment for fistula varies depending on the cause and extent of the fistula, but often involves surgical intervention combined with antibiotic therapy.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] In some cases the fistula is temporarily covered, using a fibrin glue or plug.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Catheters may be required to drain a fistula.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Surgery is often required to assure adequate drainage of the fistula (so that pus may escape without forming an abscess).
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Management involves treating any underlying causative condition.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] For example, surgical treatment of fistulae in Crohn's disease can be effective, but if the Crohn's disease itself is not treated, the rate of recurrence of the fistula is very high (well above 50%).
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] In people with kidney failure, requiring dialysis, a cimino fistula is often deliberately created in the arm by means of a short day surgery in order to permit easier withdrawal of blood for hemodialysis.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] As a radical treatment for portal hypertension, surgical creation of a portacaval fistula produces an anastomosis between the hepatic portal vein and the inferior vena cava across the omental foramen (of Winslow).
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] This spares the portal venous system from high pressure which can cause esophageal varices, caput medusae, and hemorrhoids.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] Globally, every year between 50,000 and 100,000 women are affected by fistula relating to childbirth.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] In botany, the term is most common in its adjectival forms, where it is used in binomial names to refer to species that are distinguished by hollow or tubular structures.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] *Monarda fistulosa*, for example, has tubular flowers; *Eutrochium fistulosum* has a tubular stem; *Allium fistulosum* has hollow or tubular leaves, and *Acacia seyal* subsp.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] *fistula* is the subspecies with hollow spines.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] A fistula plays a central role in William Shakespeare's play *All's Well That Ends Well*.
[src:alexis-st-martin/fistula] An arteriovenous fistula is also a main plot point in Richard Fleischer's 1966 film *Fantastic Voyage* (screenplay by Harry Kleiner), sending the miniaturized submarine inside a patient's body on an unforeseen course.
